          <div class="below-video description-box"><h3>Gangland: The Assassins (Logan Heights) - Paul Kaplan</h3><p>Gangland is one of the—if not the—most egregious peddler of ‘crimesploitation’ happily consumed in America these days.  What is ‘crimesploitation?’ (if I am lucky, I may have coined the term; I haven’t seen it anywhere nor do I find it in a Google search).  Crimesploitation is obviously a portmanteau of the words ‘crime’ and ‘exploitation,’ and it means just what is says:  a media text exploiting crime.  Like the Blaxploitation flics of the 70’s, 21st Century crimesploitation takes features of its culture object and highlights them in absurd, titillating bas-relief stereotypes (for a hefty profit).</p><p>In this case, Gangland starts before it starts: note the ‘warning’ that the show will contain ‘graphic material’ and that ‘viewer discretion is advised.’  This, of course, is an interpellation, not a warning; like all ‘parental warnings’ this disclaimer undoubtedly has the opposite effect of its (purported) intention.  The substantive material in Gangland: The Assassins (Logan Heights) is a mashup of violent images, scary words, and dramatic sounds, a delineation of ‘street terror.’  We see montages of bullet riddled bodies (are they actual victims of Logan?), photos of dozens of young Hispanic men hoisting guns (with their eyes dramatically redacted with a sharpy), graffiti tags, almost subliminally fast insertions of video of a handgun being fired (by a Logan member?), we are told by the narrator’s deep and almost sneeringly dramatic voice that ‘They’re violent hitmen.  They are Logan Heights. Respect them or die.’ As this sentence ends, we see a tattoo of a handgun pointed at us. Later we meet ‘Ghost’ who explains the attraction of being a hitman (his identity dramatically altered with a hood, dark lighting, and a raspy voice alteration).  We learn some colorful shibboleths of the land of gangs (what does it mean to be ‘out of bounds?’).  And on and on. </p><p>The problem with Gangland (and its peers such as Lockup or To Catch a Predator) is that it purports to explain gangs but actually explains nothing.  In other words, Gangland is a kind of verisimilitude—a ‘truthiness’ or perhaps a simulacrum of explanation.  Gangland is the opposite of real cultural investigation because it is nothing more than ghetto tourism, a titillating diversion into gun battles, dark alleys, drug deals, and muscled and tattooed men, all for the easy consumption of white people sitting on a couch.  Ultimately, Gangland’s (and its peers’) problem is rooted in its exploitive nature—the show’s purpose is to make money for The History Channel and its corporate overlords Disney and the Hearst Corporation.  In this sense, Gangland is much more crime than art.</p></div>          <div class="below-video tags">meta-tags</div>
          <div class="below-video user">{{user}} avatar and info</div>
