          <div class="below-video description-box"><h3>Balboa Park Pond Scandal - Paul Kaplan</h3><p>The Balboa Park Pond Water Fight became a minor scandal when the mess left by revelers turned out to damage the beloved lily pond to the tune of $10,000. Plants, lily-pads and even a few koi fish were killed because of the water fight. The scandal got juicy when mayoral candidate Bob Filner insinuated that his rival Carl DeMaio’s boyfriend Johnathon Hale was involved in the water fight. The local media repeatedly mentioned that the SDPD ‘is investigating’ the incident, although as of this writing it appears no one has been arrested, nor is it clear what crimes might have occurred. It is unlikely that anyone involved intended to hurt fish, turtles, or lily-pads (remember, most crimes require mens rea, or ‘a guilty mind’). Is it art or crime? The water fight allows us to stretch our understandings of ‘art,’ because while this silly and slightly harmful party would pass few artists’ or critics’ test for ‘art,’ it was certainly an instantiation of antagonistic relational aesthetics. The water fight resembles flash mobs and the bike-activism of ‘critical mass;’ it was probably cathartic, silly, slightly risky, and a lot of fun for the participants (I wasn’t there nor do I know any of the water fighters). To borrow from Jeff Ferrell, the water fight was probably a collective (but unconscious) reaction to the boredom of modernity. I could be wrong, but I will guess that many of the water fighters spend their days a bit buttoned up inside of cubicles in downtown San Diego. While I think some of the water fighters should probably be asked to compensate the city for the damages, the water fight was a lot more art than crime.</p></div>
